e></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FH030107%2F1"><gtr:id>7BFC46C6-D206-42A0-89EB-36D2C7BBE958</gtr:id><gtr:title>The role of sleep in off-line consolidation of meanings in newly learnt words</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/H030107/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>We encounter new words all the time, and although it may seem that learning them is relatively quick and effortless, recent work reveals a complex picture. Studies looking at learning of meaningless novel words have shown that although these are quickly memorised well enough to be recalled immediately after training, they do not become integrated in the mental dictionary for several hours or days. These effects are believed to be due to strengthening or consolidation which can occur during sleep. However, while sleep has been shown to be beneficial for learning meaningless words, little is known about its role in learning new word meanings. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>The current project aims to fill this gap in our knowledge by examining the impact of sleep on learning word meanings. This project will also measure brain activity during sleep after learning. Analysis will focus on the impact word learning has on the distribution of sleep stages, such as rapid eye movement sleep, and on other sleep-related electrophysiological events such as sleep spindles (rapid oscillations which are believed to help memory consolidation). Determining which aspects of sleep are affected by word learning will help to elucidate just how the sleeping brain consolidates newly established memories. &lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2011-03-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2010-04-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>81343</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>FDB30CDD-1F76-4D25-8D71-3B4AF6F5E7B3</gtr:id><gtr:title>Targeted memory reactivation of newly learned words during sleep triggers REM-mediated integration of new memories and existing knowledge.</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Neurobiology of learning and memory</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/7892447406695ddbe6695465f22e1441"><gtr:id>7892447406695ddbe6695465f22e1441</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Tamminen J</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>20